<h1 id="request-req-">Request (<code>req</code>)</h1>
<p>Sails is built on <a href="https://github.com/balderdashy/sails-docs/blob/master/PAGE_NEEDED.md" target="_blank">Express</a>, and uses <a href="http://nodejs.org/api/http.html" target="_blank">Node&apos;s HTTP server</a> conventions.  Because of this, you can access all of the Node and Express methods and properties on the <code>req</code> object whereever it is accessible (i.e. in your controllers, policies, and custom responses.)</p>
<p>A nice side effect of this compatibility is that, in many cases, you can paste existing Node.js code into a Sails app and it will work.  And since Sails implements a transport-agnostic request interpreter, the code in your Sails app is WebSocket-compatible as well.</p>
<p>Sails adds a few methods and properties of its own to the <code>req</code> object, like <a href="http://sailsjs.org/documentation/reference/req/req.wantsJSON.html" target="_blank"><code>req.wantsJSON</code></a> and <a href="http://sailsjs.org/documentation/reference/req/req.allParams.html" target="_blank"><code>req.allParams()</code></a>.  These features are syntactic sugar on top of the underlying implementation, and also support both HTTP and WebSockets.</p>
